tendencies of most studies on Picasso, reasserting the structure and substance of the artist's work.With compelling insight, Clark focuses on three central works—the large-scale Guitar and Mandolin on a Table (1924), The Three Dancers (1925), and The Painter and His Model (1927)—and explores Picasso's answer to Nietzsche's belief that the age-old commitment to truth was imploding in modern European culture. Masterful in its historical contextualization, Picasso and Truth rescues Picasso from the celebrity culture that trivializes his accomplishments and returns us to the tragic vision of his art—humane and appalling, naïve and difficult, in mourning for a lost nineteenth century, yet utterly exposed to the hell of Europe between the wars.Published in association with the Center for Advanced Study in the Visual Arts, National Gallery of Art, Washington, DCPlease note: All images in this ebook are presented in black and white.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh  aAbjection.  aAcademic art.  aAphorism.  aBanality (sculpture series).  aBust of a Woman (Marie-Thérèse).  aCarl Einstein.  aCimabue.  aClassicism.  aClement Greenberg.  aCollage.  aConstantin Brâncu?i.  aCubism.  aDaniel-Henry Kahnweiler.  aDe Stijl.  aDora Maar.  aEroticism.  aFacsimile.  aFalsity.  aFarce.  aFernande Olivier.  aFine art.  aFriedrich Nietzsche.  aGerhard Richter.  aGesso.  aGiorgio de Chirico.  aHorace Walpole.  aHorror vacui.  aIllusionism (art).  aJackson Pollock.  aJudith Butler.  aKitsch.  aLawrence Gowing.  aLe Figaro.  aLecture.  aLes Demoiselles d'Avignon.  aMa Jolie (Picasso, 1912).  aMaenad.  aMarc Chagall.  aMarcel Duchamp.  aMario Praz.  aMichael Fried.  aModern art.  aModernity.  aMural.  aNegative space.  aObscenity.  